 gradual globalized community starting in the 1970s, Vipond eloquently and clearly highlights the challenges posed by multicultural citizenship in a city that was dominated by Anglo-Protestants. Contrary to recent well-documented anti-immigrant rhetoric in the media, Making a Global City celebrates one of the world’s most multicultural cities while stressing the fact that public schools are a vital tool in integrating and accepting immigrants and children in liberal democracies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipzOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducation and statezOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMulticulturalismzOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic schoolszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aToope, Stephen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262442940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442624429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442624429.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles